					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">rainwarrior wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I don't know if my zapper is defective or different in some way from other zappers, but I don't have any others here to test at the moment.<br /></div> Hm. So, it <em>is</em> an electrolytic capacitor inside the zapper there, and so probably has a typical Equivalent Series Resistance of somewhere around 10Î©, give or take.<br /><br />So if you somehow manage to keep your finger right on the near edge of the make/break threshold, and you manage to intentionally/accidentally use muscle tremors to keep it making contact with a 1% duty cycle, you'll manage to keep the voltage across the capacitor in the middle of the relevant range for the 74HC368 to toggle between logic 1 and 0.<br /><br />But given how much effort this takes, I have to wonder if this:<br /><div class="quotetitle">rainwarrior wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I analyzed Duck Hunt's trigger code a while back, and it was definitely doing software filtering to reject noise like this<br /></div> is because the original famicom zapper could be missing the capacitor altogether?</div>

